# Cicero Speech — Revolutionary Artefact

## Target Audience
Cicero addressed the Roman Senate, influential nobles, and indirectly the Roman people, warning them about Lucius Sergius Catilina’s conspiracy against Rome.

## Purpose
The speech aimed to expose Catiline’s plot, protect the Republic, and convince senators to take urgent action against internal threats.

## Effect / Why Revolutionary
It strengthened senatorial authority, stopped a rebellion, and showed how powerful rhetoric could defend the Republic during political crisis in Rome.

## When
Marcus Tullius Cicero delivered the First Catilinarian Oration in 63 BCE, during a time of serious political tension in Rome.

## Key Idea
Rome was still the Roman Republic, meaning it was governed by elected officials like senators and consuls, not emperors.

## Evidence
“I have always been of the opinion that unpopularity earned by doing what is right is not unpopularity at all, but glory.”  
— Marcus Tullius Cicero
